ðŸ”¸ Box Model (ðŸ”¥ MOST IMPORTANT)
	21. What is the CSS box model?
	The CSS box model explains how every HTML element is treated as a box in a webpage.
	It controls the size, spacing, and layout of elements.
	One-line interview answer:
		The CSS box model defines the layout of an element using content, padding, border, and margin.
	
	22. What are the components of the box model?
	The CSS box model has four components:
		1. Content â€“ actual text or image
		2. Padding â€“ space inside the border
		3. Border â€“ outline around padding
		4. Margin â€“ space outside the border
	Order:
	Content â†’ Padding â†’ Border â†’ Margin
	One-line interview answer:
		The components of the box model are content, padding, border, and margin.
	
	23. Difference between margin and padding?
	Margin	Padding
	Space outside the border	Space inside the border
	Creates space between elements	Creates space inside element
	Transparent	Affects background color
	Simple interview answer:
		Margin controls outer spacing, while padding controls inner spacing.
		
21. What is border?
A border is a line that surrounds the padding and content of an element.
It is used to separate elements visually.
Example:

div {
  border: 2px solid black;
}
One-line interview answer:
	A border is the outline around an elementâ€™s content and padding.

22. What is box-sizing?
box-sizing controls how the total width and height of an element are calculated.
It tells the browser whether padding and border should be included in the size or not.
Example:

box-sizing: border-box;
One-line interview answer:
	Box-sizing defines how an elementâ€™s width and height are calculated.

23. Difference between content-box and border-box?
content-box (default)	border-box
Width includes only content	Width includes content + padding + border
Padding & border add extra size	Size remains fixed
Harder to manage layouts	Easier for layouts âœ…
Example:

box-sizing: content-box;
box-sizing: border-box;

ðŸ”¸ Display & Positioning
	27. What is the display property?
	The display property controls how an element is shown on the page.
	It defines the elementâ€™s layout behavior.
	Common values:
		â€¢ block
		â€¢ inline
		â€¢ inline-block
		â€¢ none
		â€¢ flex
		â€¢ grid
	One-line interview answer:
		The display property defines how an element is displayed and laid out on a webpage.
	
	28. Difference between display: none and visibility: hidden?
	display: none	visibility: hidden
	Element is removed from layout	Element is invisible but space remains
	No space occupied	Space is still occupied
	Not visible	Not visible
	Simple interview answer:
		display: none removes the element completely, while visibility: hidden hides it but keeps its space.
	
	29. What is position property?
	The position property controls how an element is positioned on the page.
	Common values:
		â€¢ static
		â€¢ relative
		â€¢ absolute
		â€¢ fixed
		â€¢ sticky
	One-line interview answer:
		The position property is used to control the placement of elements on a webpage.
27. Difference between static, relative, absolute, fixed, and sticky?
	â€¢ static
Default position. Element stays in normal flow.
	â€¢ relative
Positioned relative to itself using top, left, etc.
	â€¢ absolute
Positioned relative to nearest positioned parent.
	â€¢ fixed
Positioned relative to viewport (does not move on scroll).
	â€¢ sticky
Acts relative at first, then becomes fixed on scroll.
One-line interview answer:
	Static is default, relative moves from itself, absolute is positioned to parent, fixed is fixed to screen, and sticky sticks on scroll.

28. What is z-index?
z-index controls the vertical stacking order of elements.
Higher z-index appears on top of lower ones.
âš  Works only on positioned elements.
Example:

z-index: 10;
One-line interview answer:
	z-index controls which element appears on top when elements overlap.

29. What is overflow?
The overflow property controls what happens when content exceeds the container size.
Values:
	â€¢ hidden
	â€¢ scroll
	â€¢ auto
	â€¢ visible
One-line interview answer:
	Overflow controls how extra content is handled when it goes outside the container.

ðŸ”¸ Colors, Units & Sizing
	33. Different ways to define colors in CSS?
	Colors in CSS can be defined in multiple ways:
		1. Color names
red, blue, green
		2. Hexadecimal
#ff0000
		3. RGB
rgb(255, 0, 0)
		4. RGBA (with transparency)
rgba(255, 0, 0, 0.5)
		5. HSL
hsl(0, 100%, 50%)
	One-line interview answer:
		CSS colors can be defined using names, hex, RGB, RGBA, and HSL values.
	
	34. Difference between px, %, em, rem?
	Unit	Meaning
	px	Fixed size
	%	Relative to parent
	em	Relative to parent font size
	rem	Relative to root (html) font size
	Simple interview answer:
		px is fixed, % is relative to parent, em depends on parent font size, and rem depends on root font size.
	
	35. What is viewport unit (vh, vw)?
	Viewport units are relative to the screen size.
		â€¢ 1vh = 1% of viewport height
		â€¢ 1vw = 1% of viewport width
	Example:
	
	height: 100vh;
width: 100vw;
	One-line interview answer:
		vh and vw are viewport units used to size elements based on screen height and width.
33. What is opacity?
opacity controls the transparency of an element.
	â€¢ Value ranges from 0 to 1
	â€¢ 0 = fully transparent
	â€¢ 1 = fully visible
Example:

opacity: 0.5;
One-line interview answer:
	Opacity controls how transparent an element appears.

34. What is background property?
The background property is used to style an elementâ€™s background.
It can set:
	â€¢ background color
	â€¢ background image
	â€¢ background position
	â€¢ background repeat
	â€¢ background size
Example:

background: red;
background-image: url("img.jpg");
One-line interview answer:
	The background property is used to control an elementâ€™s background color or image.

35. Difference between max-width and width?
width	max-width
Sets fixed width	Sets maximum width
Can overflow on small screens	Responsive-friendly âœ…
Not flexible	Flexible
Simple interview answer:
	width sets a fixed size, while max-width limits the maximum size and allows responsiveness.

ðŸ”¸ Flexbox & Layout (ðŸ”¥ Very Important)
	39. What is Flexbox?
	Flexbox (Flexible Box Layout) is a CSS layout model used to align, arrange, and distribute space between elements easily.
	It is mainly used for one-dimensional layouts (row or column).
	One-line interview answer:
		Flexbox is a CSS layout system used to align and arrange elements in a row or column.
	
	40. What is flex container and flex items?
		â€¢ Flex container
The parent element where display: flex is applied.
		â€¢ Flex items
The child elements inside the flex container.
	Example:
	
	.container {
  display: flex;
}
	One-line interview answer:
		The element with display flex is the flex container, and its children are flex items.
	
	41. Difference between justify-content and align-items?
		â€¢ justify-content
Aligns items along the main axis (horizontal by default).
		â€¢ align-items
Aligns items along the cross axis (vertical by default).
	Example:
	
	justify-content: center;
align-items: center;
	One-line interview answer:
		justify-content aligns items horizontally, while align-items aligns items vertically.
39. What is flex-direction?
flex-direction defines the direction in which flex items are placed.
Values:
	â€¢ row (default)
	â€¢ row-reverse
	â€¢ column
	â€¢ column-reverse
Example:

flex-direction: row;
One-line interview answer:
	flex-direction controls the direction of flex items.

40. What is flex-wrap?
flex-wrap controls whether flex items wrap to the next line when there is no space.
Values:
	â€¢ nowrap (default)
	â€¢ wrap
	â€¢ wrap-reverse
Example:

flex-wrap: wrap;
One-line interview answer:
	flex-wrap allows flex items to move to the next line when needed.

41. What is gap in flexbox?
gap defines the space between flex items.
It avoids using margins.
Example:

gap: 20px;
One-line interview answer:
	gap is used to create spacing between flex items.

42. Difference between Flexbox and Grid?
Flexbox	Grid
One-dimensional	Two-dimensional
Row OR column	Rows AND columns
Best for small layouts	Best for page layouts
One-line interview answer:
	Flexbox is for one-dimensional layouts, while Grid is for two-dimensional layouts.

ðŸ”¸ Responsive Design (VERY IMPORTANT)
	46. What is responsive design?
	Responsive design means creating websites that work well on all devices like mobile, tablet, and desktop.
	The layout automatically adjusts according to screen size.
	One-line interview answer:
		Responsive design makes a website adapt to different screen sizes.
	
	47. What is a media query?
	A media query is used in CSS to apply styles based on screen size or device type.
	It helps in creating responsive designs.
	Example:
	
	@media (max-width: 768px) {
  body {
    background: lightblue;
  }
}
	One-line interview answer:
		Media queries apply CSS based on screen size or device conditions.
	
	48. How do you make a website responsive?
	A website can be made responsive by:
		â€¢ Using media queries
		â€¢ Using flexbox or grid
		â€¢ Using relative units like %, rem, vh, vw
		â€¢ Using responsive images
		â€¢ Using the viewport meta tag
	Simple interview answer:
		We make websites responsive using media queries, flexible layouts, and relative units.
46. What is mobile-first design?
Mobile-first design means designing the website for mobile devices first, and then adding styles for larger screens like tablets and desktops.
It improves performance and user experience on mobile.
One-line interview answer:
	Mobile-first design means building a website for mobile screens first and then scaling up.

47. What is the viewport meta tag?
The viewport meta tag controls how a webpage is displayed on different screen sizes, especially on mobile devices.
It helps make the website responsive.
Example:

<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
One-line interview answer:
	The viewport meta tag helps webpages adapt to different screen sizes.

ðŸ”¸ CSS Specificity & Important Rules
	51. What is CSS specificity?
	CSS specificity decides which CSS rule is applied when multiple rules target the same element.
	The rule with higher specificity wins.
	One-line interview answer:
		CSS specificity determines which style rule is applied to an element.
	
	52. Order of CSS priority?
	CSS follows this priority order (highest to lowest):
		1. !important
		2. Inline CSS
		3. ID selector
		4. Class selector
		5. Element selector
		6. Universal selector
	If specificity is same, the last written rule wins.
	One-line interview answer:
		CSS priority is based on importance, specificity, and order of rules.
	
	53. What is !important?
	!important forces a CSS rule to override all other rules, ignoring specificity.
	Example:
	
	color: red !important;
	âš  Should be used only when necessary.
	One-line interview answer:
		!important forces a CSS rule to apply over all others.
51. Inline vs internal vs external CSS priority?
The priority order is:
	1. Inline CSS (highest priority)
	2. Internal CSS
	3. External CSS (lowest priority)
âš  If !important is used, it overrides all.
One-line interview answer:
	Inline CSS has the highest priority, followed by internal CSS, and then external CSS.

52. What happens if two styles conflict?
When two styles apply to the same element:
	1. Higher specificity wins
	2. If specificity is same, the last written rule wins
	3. !important overrides everything

ðŸ”¸ Transitions, Animations & Effects
	56. What is transition?
	A CSS transition is used to create a smooth change from one style to another when an event happens (like hover).
	Example:
	
	button {
  transition: background-color 0.3s;
}
	One-line interview answer:
		A transition smoothly changes a CSS property when an event occurs.
	
	57. What is animation?
	A CSS animation allows an element to change styles automatically over time without user action.
	It uses keyframes.
	Example:
	
	@keyframes move {
  from { left: 0; }
  to { left: 100px; }
}
	One-line interview answer:
		Animation changes element styles over time using keyframes.
	
	58. Difference between transition and animation?
	Transition	Animation
	Needs user action	Runs automatically
	Simple start â†’ end	Multiple steps
	Uses duration only	Uses keyframes
	One-line interview answer:
		Transition needs an event to start, while animation runs automatically using keyframes.
56. What is transform?
The transform property is used to change the shape, size, or position of an element.
Common transformations:
	â€¢ translate (move)
	â€¢ scale (resize)
	â€¢ rotate (rotate)
	â€¢ skew (tilt)
Example:

transform: scale(1.2);
One-line interview answer:
	Transform is used to move, rotate, scale, or skew an element.

57. What is box-shadow?
box-shadow adds a shadow effect around an element.
It improves visual depth and design.
Example:

box-shadow: 2px 2px 5px gray;
One-line interview answer:
	box-shadow is used to add shadow effects around elements.

ðŸ”¸ Advanced-Basic (Good to Know)
	61. What is CSS Grid?
	CSS Grid is a layout system used to design two-dimensional layouts using rows and columns.
	It is best for page layouts.
	One-line interview answer:
		CSS Grid is a layout system used to create two-dimensional layouts with rows and columns.
	
	62. What are CSS variables?
	CSS variables are used to store reusable values like colors, fonts, or spacing.
	They make CSS easy to maintain.
	Example:
	
	--main-color: blue;
	One-line interview answer:
		CSS variables store reusable values that can be used throughout the stylesheet.
	
	63. What is :root?
	:root is a pseudo-class that represents the root element (html).
	It is commonly used to define global CSS variables.
	Example:
	
	:root {
  --main-color: red;
}
	One-line interview answer:
		:root is used to define global CSS variables.
	61. What is calc() function?
	The calc() function is used to perform calculations in CSS.
	It allows combining different units like %, px, rem.
	Example:
	
	width: calc(100% - 50px);
	One-line interview answer:
		calc() is used to calculate CSS values using different units.
	
	62. What is object-fit?
	object-fit controls how images or videos fit inside a container.
	Common values:
		â€¢ cover
		â€¢ contain
		â€¢ fill
	Example:
	
	object-fit: cover;
	One-line interview answer:
		object-fit controls how images or videos are resized within their container.
	
	63. What is cursor property?
	The cursor property changes the mouse pointer style when hovering over an element.
	Example:
	
	cursor: pointer;
	One-line interview answer:
		The cursor property controls the mouse pointer style.
61. What is float?
The float property is used to move an element to the left or right and allow text to wrap around it.
It was mainly used for layouts before Flexbox and Grid.
Example:

float: left;
One-line interview answer:
	Float is used to align elements left or right and allow content to wrap around them.

62. What is clear?
The clear property is used to stop elements from floating next to floated elements.
Values: left, right, both
Example:

clear: both;
One-line interview answer:
	Clear prevents elements from wrapping around floated elements.

63. What is overflow: auto?
overflow: auto adds scrollbars only when needed if content exceeds the container size.
Example:

overflow: auto;
One-line interview answer:
	overflow auto shows scrollbars only when content overflows.

64. What is position: sticky?
position: sticky makes an element behave like relative first and then stick to a position when scrolling.
Commonly used for sticky headers.
Example:

position: sticky;
top: 0;
One-line interview answer:
	Position sticky makes an element stick to the screen after scrolling.

